\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Market demand curve:
\series default
 the set of consumers arranged in inverse ordering from the person with
 the highest willingness to pay (WTP) to the person with the lowest WTP
 for a commodity.
 It is aggregated from Marshallian demands.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Market supply curve:
\series default
 the set of producers arranged in order from the firm willing to produce
 at the lowest price to the firm demanding the highest price to produce
 a good.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Consumer surplus:
\series default
 the difference between the maximum value that a consumer is willing to
 pay for a commodity and the market price of that commodity.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Producer surplus:
\series default
 what the producer receives for goods in excess of the cost of production.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A competitive market maximizes the sum of producer and consumer surplus:
 all gains from trade are realized; all transactions that benefit both parties
 occur; no transactions occur that do not benefit both parties.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
How to calculate consumer and producer surplus?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
quad
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote the equilibrium price before a price change as 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mkt}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consumer surplus is the region below the demand curve and above the price,
 and is equal to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{p_{mkt}}^{\infty}D(p)\mathrm{d}p.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{min}$
\end_inset

 denote the price required to supply 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 units of the good.
 Producer surplus is the region below the market price and above the supply
 curve, and is equal to:
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Usually 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{min}=0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{p_{min}}^{p_{mkt}}S(p)\mathrm{d}p.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose that there is a change in the price paid by consumers (from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mkt}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{C}$
\end_inset

) and received by suppliers (from 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{mkt}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p^{S}$
\end_inset

).
 Then, the change in consumer surplus is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{p^{C}}^{\infty}D(p)\mathrm{d}p-\int_{p_{mkt}}^{\infty}D(p)\mathrm{d}p=\int_{p_{mkt}}^{p^{C}}D(p)\mathrm{d}p.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The change in producer surplus is:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{p_{min}}^{p^{S}}S(p)\mathrm{d}p-\int_{p_{min}}^{p_{mkt}}S(p)\mathrm{d}p=\int_{p_{mkt}}^{p^{S}}S(P)dP.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Deadweight loss
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
quad
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Deadweight loss is the difference between the total producer and consumer
 surplus and the maximized producer and consumer surplus in competitive
 market.
 There is deadweight loss whenever the quantity is not equal to the quantity
 in the competitive market, and the gains from trading are not maximized
 (either unrealized beneficial trading or harmful trading).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The deadweight loss only depends on the quantity consumed.
 The price alone determines the transfer between consumer and producer but
 does not affect the total surplus.
\end_layout

