\begin_layout Section
General Equilibrium in Exchange Economy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
quad
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two consumers, A and B, two goods, F and S.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
They have endowment:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{A}=(E_{A}^{F},E_{A}^{S})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{B}=(E_{B}^{F},E_{B}^{S})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Without trade, they each consume their endowment:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{A}=E_{A}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{B}=E_{B}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With trade, the only constraint is that market clears :
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{A}^{F}+X_{B}^{F}=E_{A}^{F}+E_{B}^{F}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{A}^{S}+X_{B}^{S}=E_{A}^{S}+E_{B}^{S}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Walras' Law: when one market clears the other one also clears.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve for the equilibrium, first derive each consumer's Marshallian demand,
 and then apply the market clearing condition to solve for the equilibrium
 prices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Pareto Efficiency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a Pareto efficient allocation, it is not possible to make one person
 better o without making at least one other person worse off.
 At a Pareto efficient allocation, all gains from trade are exhausted.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At a Pareto efficient allocation, the indifference curves of A and B will
 be tangent.
 The set of points that satisfy this criterion comprise the 
\series bold
Contract Curve
\series default
 (CC).
 On the contract curve the MRS of the two consumers are equal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{\partial U/\partial F}{\partial U/\partial S}\right)_{A}=\left(\frac{\partial U/\partial F}{\partial U/\partial S}\right)_{B}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Welfare Theorems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
quad
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
First Welfare Theorem:
\series default
 If
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C1) No externalities
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C2) Perfect competition
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C3) No transaction costs
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
(C4) Full information
\begin_inset VSpace smallskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then competitive equilibrium is Pareto efficient.
\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Second Welfare Theorem:
\series default
 Providing that preferences are convex and conditions C1-C4 are satisfied,
 any Pareto efficient allocation can be supported as a market equilibrium.
 (there is no intrinsic trade-off between equity and efficiency.)
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second welfare theorem indicates that we can achieve any allocation
 of resources 
\series bold
on the contract curve
\series default
 through lump-sum distributions.
 That is, a planner can achieve 
\series bold
any competitive equilibrium
\series default
 she desires through lump-sum distributions, but cannot achieve points off
 the contract curve as long as agents are free to trade
\series bold
.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
A planner will never be able to achieve an allocation that is not on the
 contract curve without banning trade outright.
 If she tried to achieve a non-equilibrium point, agents will just trade
 with each other and converge to an equilibrium on the contract curve.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
International Trade and Comparative Advantage
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
quad
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
International trade relaxes the constraint that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

no more goods can be demanded/consumed than the economy is endowed with,
 and the sum of the consumption of both parties cannot exceed the total
 endowment.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The movement from autarky (no trade) to free trade usually expands the Home's
 budget set, and therefore Home can achieve higher utility.
 The gap between production and consumption reflects the gains from trade.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Gains from trade come entirely from differences between countries.
 There is no gains from trade if relative prices are the same under autarky
 and trade:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\frac{P_{F}}{P_{S}}\right)_{A}=\left(\frac{P_{F}}{P_{S}}\right)_{W}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Countries have 
\shape italic
comparative advantage
\shape default
 if the relative prices in autarky differ from the world price, and this
 may be due to preferences, technology, or endowments.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Principle of comparative advantage: as long as relative prices differ between
 two countries, both countries experience gains from trade.
 Because trade allows Home to specialize in production of the good in which
 it is has comparative advantage relative to the rest of the world, and
 use that good to trade for other goods in the world market.
\begin_inset VSpace medskip
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
International 
\series default
trade is Pareto improvement relative to initial endowment but not necessarily
 Pareto improvement relative to autarky (in the sense of 
\series bold
within-country trade
\series default
).
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
See the ADH diagram in Lecture 14.
 In particular, some parties within the economy might be worse-off than
 in a situation with only 
\series bold
within-country
\series default
 trade, but will still be better-off than in a situation where they are
 forced to consume their initial endowments.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 But through an appropriate set of transfers, we can both exhaust all gains
 from trade and achieve any Pareto efficient allocation desired.
 
\end_layout

